John Edward: Language Skills are Necessities for Global Citizens
Scottish independent schools have a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other excellent exam results. Individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community activities just underscore this.
These schools have more than 30,000 pupils throughout Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), and strive to provide their pupils and parents with the best possible level of service.
Independent schools are preparing their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individually tailored school curricula, we note that modern languages are still popular and sought after subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight into his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is a significant observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s tests show that languages are in the top of the table, with the highest rate of success being achieved by independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved the best scores of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that the highest score A was achieved by 72% of students of Mandarin, 72% of students of German, 69% of students of French and 63% of students of Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by students are considered in the curricula of independent and other schools as well as subjects of STEM (science, technology, technical disciplines and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17 per cent of the language skills are insufficient for reasons that employers refer to as vacant jobs.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require language, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Whether a person chooses any career, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future that he has such a lifelong skill.
With the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a multilingual person automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to lead a conversation, with a single language spoken by a two-digit French-speaking group of 15 percent of people.
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school is different by the language it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important to the UK in the outlook for 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child is interested in, he will always have a choice of several languages at independent schools with teachers who are experts in the given field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to ensuring an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what awaits them in the future.
At this point, it cannot be denied that languages are essential for the future of the country in a global business environment, so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should, in fact, be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and attractions to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
