Harvard students take part in a course that is designed to teach them enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has led all its students to sleep more, in an effort to fight the growing culture of macho studies overnight when students are not sleeping and are encouraged to take caffeine.
Academicians have found that students at the world’s most famous university are often helpless when it comes to the basics of self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and a female hospital, which is thought to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the day, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me that only now, in my last year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first presented this year, explains to students the basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to launch the course after finding that the students were really not asleep during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of student circuits where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In the other part, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
However, we think they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the effects of smoking cigarettes on health,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in “study all night” still exists, he added that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean there is also a growing problem of lack of sleep.
Enough sleep of good quality should be a student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even to prevent accumulation, because sleep deprivation switches the brain to hunger mode, so a person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Ceisler design a course that last year, during his first year at Harvard, graduated from one of his classes.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the entire course.
He hopes that the next step will require all graduate students to complete a similar study program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor advised students to consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can resolve your circadian rhythm problems.
